      "writtenOn": "2018-02-16T23:42:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is really far out and more of a v2 thing, but if the webcam\u0027s \u0027native\u0027 res is something a lot bigger than our required dimenisions, like 1080p, I wonder if we could compare the speeds of:\n\na. using current path that might end up rescaling it to a particular resolution that we require\nb. advertising that native dimension directly, and passing it through to android framework\nc. (b) but we also rescale it ourselves back to our android resolutions with libyuv or opengl magic.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 361,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 365,
        "endChar": 17
      },
      "revId": "ad53461b2b8d0db2977ae204ea0cf770d2b542b4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5015729b_f6cb3b0c",
        "filename": "android/android-emu/android/camera/camera-capture-windows.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 365,
      "author": {
        "id": 1233742
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-20T22:29:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I think it\u0027s worth benchmarking.  The QEMU transport doesn\u0027t appear to be a bottleneck, so sending the highest available resolution through may be the best.  The biggest pain point is that changing resolutions requires restarting the camera, which can add several seconds of latency when taking a picture or toggling between photo/video.  Changing resolutions here (and in the other cameras) requires some reconfiguring, and may be slow, so I\u0027m leaning towards a custom scaler implemented either alongside convert_frame or within the QEMU camera so that we can change resolutions on-the-fly.",
      "parentUuid": "5b35b797_289ea34e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 361,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 365,
        "endChar": 17
      },
      "revId": "ad53461b2b8d0db2977ae204ea0cf770d2b542b4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
