        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-16T23:33:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I wonder if it could be worth using all IMFSample::GetBufferCount buffers here to take advantage of any async flipping setup that might exist, if it ends up making readFrame faster.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 653,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 653,
        "endChar": 48
      },
      "revId": "ad53461b2b8d0db2977ae204ea0cf770d2b542b4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8cc9f5bd_cb1be937",
        "filename": "android/android-emu/android/camera/camera-capture-windows.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 653,
      "author": {
        "id": 1233742
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-20T22:29:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "For video, I\u0027ve never seen more than buffer used.  It\u0027s one of those features that MF supports to be super flexible.  The only time I\u0027ve seen multiple buffers used was for audio, where there are multiple buffers to prevent allocating more memory when the data is too large to fit into one.\n\nIn most of these cases, the caller simply calls sample-\u003eConvertToContiguousBuffer(\u0026spBuffer) which concats all the buffers together.  Come to think of it, that\u0027s probably a good idea here-- there may be a strange webcam out there that treats planar formats as different buffers.",
      "parentUuid": "f507a169_42ec0a4f",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 653,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 653,
        "endChar": 48
      },
      "revId": "ad53461b2b8d0db2977ae204ea0cf770d2b542b4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "51090ee1_5de6dc11",
        "filename": "android/android-emu/android/camera/camera-capture-windows.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 676,
      "author": {
        "id": 1082465
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-16T23:33:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Should we memcpy and unlock first, then convert_frame in order to give the \n underlying webcam capture more time to continue reading out frames?\n\nThough convert_frame_fast should be pretty fast now so it might not matter so much.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 671,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 676,
        "endChar": 29
      },
      "revId": "ad53461b2b8d0db2977ae204ea0cf770d2b542b4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4c050a70_137fc6db",
        "filename": "android/android-emu/android/camera/camera-capture-windows.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 676,
      "author": {
        "id": 1233742
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-20T22:29:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think doing an extra memcpy will do more harm than good.  Internally sources use a IMFVideoSampleAllocator to create and recycle samples on-demand, which can have many outstanding samples if necessary-- returning the sample immediately is not a big concern.",
      "parentUuid": "51090ee1_5de6dc11",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 671,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 676,
        "endChar": 29
